# VERSION
v1.26.1

# Changelog
- v1.26.1
    - **Field-dictionary sources moved out of `config/` into `scripts/`** ‚Äî the AmazingData field-dictionary source tree (`config/field_dictionary/amazing_data/` ‚Üí `scripts/field_dictionary/amazing_data/`) was relocated. `.gitignore` line `/app/projects/phoenixA/config/*` had been silently dropping the maintenance `.py` scripts in `config/` (only the 6 data files were force-tracked); moving under the tracked `scripts/` tree brings the maintenance scripts (`regenerate_seed_sql.py`, `update_version.py`) into version control and removes `config/`'s mixed "project config vs. build-time dictionary sources" conflation. No Go code change (the DAO reads the `govern.data_*_dictionary` DB tables at runtime, never this directory); the move is build-time only.
    - **`regenerate_seed_sql.py` corrected to match the layered migration reality** ‚Äî previously emitted the old `0013_seed_amazing_data_field_dictionary.sql` filename with bare table names (`DELETE FROM data_field_dictionary`), diverging from the committed `0004_govern_seed.sql` (schema-qualified `govern.*`). Now outputs `0004_govern_seed.sql` with `govern.`-qualified DELETE/INSERT and a header pointing at the new `scripts/field_dictionary/amazing_data/*.jsonl` source path; `out_dir` switched to `Path(__file__).resolve().parent` so the script is move-proof. Verified: re-running it reproduces the committed `0004_govern_seed.sql` byte-for-byte (the only working-tree diff is the regenerated header source-path comment line).
    - **`generate_field_dictionary_from_docs.py` stripped of seed-SQL writing** ‚Äî the bootstrap generator (SDK docs ‚Üí JSONL) previously also wrote its own seed migration in the stale format (`0013_...sql`, bare table names, `contract_version=2026-06-25`), conflicting with `regenerate_seed_sql.py` and drifting. Removed the `write_seed_migration` function, its call, the `migration_dir`, and the now-dead SQL helpers (`sql_string`/`sql_bool`/`sql_number`/`sql_json`); `out_dir` repointed to `scripts/field_dictionary/amazing_data`; `CONTRACT_VERSION` bumped to `2026-06-27` to match the committed JSONL. Responsibilities are now single-source: this script produces JSONL only; `regenerate_seed_sql.py` is the sole JSONL‚Üíseed-SQL converter.
    - **Deleted two one-shot fix scripts** ‚Äî `fix_dictionary.py` / `fix_all_dictionaries.py` were duplicate copies of the same comp_type_scope/label cleanup logic (one targeting `financial_statement`, the other `corporate_action`/`equity_structure`); their remediation is already baked into the committed JSONL (only 80 rows carry `review_status=fixed_20260627`, all in `financial_statement`; `fix_all` never took effect on its targets). The field-dictionary rebuild chain is `JSONL ‚Üí regenerate_seed_sql.py ‚Üí 0004_govern_seed.sql ‚Üí migration`, which does not depend on the fix scripts, so deletion is safe.
    - **README synced** ‚Äî `config/field_dictionary` references ‚Üí `scripts/field_dictionary`; the maintenance-scripts table now lists only `regenerate_seed_sql.py` and `update_version.py`; added a note that field-content edits go directly into the JSONL rows followed by `regenerate_seed_sql.py`.
- v1.26.0
    - **Datawarehouse layering refactor: single datasource + multi-schema search_path** ‚Äî split the ODS landing tables, derived/processed tables, and PhoenixA-owned governance tables that were previously mixed in a single `security_dev` schema into separate PostgreSQL schemas by warehouse layer (ods / dwd / govern), accessed uniformly through a single datasource's comma-separated `search_path`. No datasource split, no DAO registration changes. Design doc: `docs/2026-06-29 DATAWAREHOUSE_LAYERING_AND_SCHEMA_REFACTOR.md`.
    - **Depends on infra v0.18.4**: `go.mod` enables `replace github.com/grand-thief-cash/chaos/app/infra/go/application => ../../infra/go/application` and re-runs `go mod vendor` to consume its multi-schema fixes (CREATE SCHEMA comma-split + hoisted before migrations, SET search_path inside the migration transaction, `_migrations` tracking table qualified with the first schema).
    - **config/config.yaml**: `postgres_gorm.data_sources.security.schema` changed from `security_dev` to `ods,dwd,govern,kg,public`. The datasource name stays `security` (`GetDB("security")` is an exact map-key lookup, so no `NewXxxDao("security")` registration needs to change).
    - **migrations/postgresql/security/**: the original 15 bare-name migrations (0001~0015, all landing in `security_dev` via implicit search_path) are rewritten into 4 schema-qualified layered migrations:
        - `0001_ods.sql` (14 tables): taxonomy_category / taxonomy_security_map / industry_constituent / industry_weight / industry_daily / financial_statement / corporate_action / bars_stock_zh_a_daily_{nf,hfq} / bars_index_zh_a_daily_nf / bars_ext_baostock_stock_zh_a_daily / adjust_factor / long_hu_bang / equity_structure. Each file runs `CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS ods` + `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ods.xxx`.
        - `0002_dwd.sql` (1 table): taxonomy_category_derived_flags.
        - `0003_govern.sql` (7 tables + 1 view): security_registry / strategy_run_summary / strategy_run_artifact / data_dataset_dictionary / data_field_dictionary / data_enum_dictionary / data_field_coverage_observation + govern.v_data_field_dictionary_active.
        - `0004_govern_seed.sql`: the former 0013 256KB AmazingData field-dictionary seed data, with table names schema-qualified to `govern.*`; uses `DELETE WHERE source=... AND contract_version=...` + `INSERT` for re-entrancy.
        - All 59 `CREATE INDEX` statements now carry `IF NOT EXISTS` (including 13 that the former 0012/0014 omitted); migrations are fully idempotent.
        - The former 0003 `trade_date` DATE type change is folded directly into CREATE TABLE (fresh reload needs no ALTER); the former 0004 storage backfill is dropped (on fresh reload tables are created directly on the correct tablespace, so backfill is redundant).
        - **Prerequisite**: with the former 0004 removed there is no backfill fallback ‚Äî before reload, a superuser must pre-create `CREATE TABLESPACE warm_storage LOCATION '...'`, otherwise every `TABLESPACE warm_storage` clause fails.
    - **model / DAO table-name mapping**: all `TableName()` methods now return schema-qualified names (ODS‚Üí`ods.`, DWD‚Üí`dwd.`, Govern‚Üí`govern.`, kg unchanged at `kg.`); `dao/table_resolver.go` `BarsTableName` / `BarsExtTableName` gain an `ods.` prefix; bare-name SQL in `field_dictionary_dao.go` / `catalog_coverage_dao.go` / `field_coverage_dao.go` / `taxonomy_dao.go` (three-table JOIN) / `schema_dao.go` (domainAllowList) / `corporate_action_dao.go` / `financial_statement_dao.go` / `equity_structure_dao.go` is all schema-qualified. The schema enumeration in `catalog_dao.go` and `catalog_service.go` changed from `["public","kg","security_dev","security"]` to `["public","kg","ods","dwd","govern"]`.
    - **Tests**: updated assertions in `model_test.go` / `catalog_dao_test.go` / `write_buffer_test.go` to the qualified names (strict `!=`, not weakened). `go build ./...`, `go vet ./...`, `go test ./...` all green. End-to-end DB validation (throwaway database): all 4 migrations run twice cleanly (idempotency confirmed); tables land as ods 14 / dwd 1 / govern 7 + view; seed data does not double on re-run (dataset=3 / field=565 / enum=56).
- v1.25.1
    - **FieldMeta carries enum_ref end-to-end**
        - Added `EnumRef` field to `FieldMeta` in `internal/model/query_response.go` so flat query responses advertise which enum backs each field.
        - Populated `EnumRef` in `fieldMetasFromResolved` (in `financial_statement_service.go`, shared by `corporate_action_service.go` and `equity_structure_service.go`) from the already-resolved `ResolvedField.EnumRef`.
        - Lets BI clients (cthulhu via artemis) render enum code ‚Üí label_zh without a separate field-discovery round-trip per cell.
